					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">TGM3 is a strange one, since it relies on Type X hardware, similarly to most other newer arcade games, such as Street Fighter IV.<br />The game itself is not a PCB, it's just a hard drive and a USB dongle or something like that. I never really got into the Type X series of &quot;arcade hardware&quot;, since it is literally just a Windows PC with a specific hardware configuration. I'm not really interested in that stuff.<br /><br />I don't know when you were on TC, but I bought my TGM2 PCB around three years ago (just before the game attracted new attention via AGDQ), and the price point has grown to nearly three times what I paid since then (and I paid a lot, too). It's definitely one of the most expensive bare arcade PCBs out there.</div>

